<TITLE> Uganda says LRA rebels violate truce, talks still on </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KAMPALA, Feb 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Uganda accused northern Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) rebels on Sunday of `blatant violations' of a truce to end their 20-year civil war, but it said peace talks would continue in neighbouring southern Sudan. "We have received reports of attacks by the LRA and movement towards the Central African Republic," the government's top negotiator, Internal Affairs Minister Ruhakana Rugunda told a news conference. "These are blatant violations of the cessations of hostilities agreement." He said government officials would still attend talks scheduled to resume in south Sudan's capital Juba on Monday. Uganda says south Sudanese officials have complained of LRA attacks killing scores of people in recent weeks, and that it has received reports of LRA rebels moving from camps on the border between south Sudan and Democratic Republic of Congo. "This is a situation that is completely unacceptable to government," Rugunda said. Kampala has given LRA leader Joseph Kony, who is wanted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), until Feb. 28 to sign a peace deal or risk returning to war. Negotiations are due to resume on Monday, when the parties are expected to sign a partial agreement on reconciliation and accountability. They will then tackle the thorny topics including disarmament and reintegration. "We will soon, after arriving in Juba, embark on a crucial stage of the talks and we, in agreement with the LRA, will announce when the date for a permanent ceasefire will start," Rugunda said. Rebel delegates could not reached for comment as they had reportedly travelled to the Congo border to meet Ko
